{
  "text": "Part 2 is devoted to the study of surfaces with p g = q = 1, K 2 = g = 3 and a pencil |G| of curves of genus 2. Xiao constructs them in [CITATION_1] by using Jacobian fibrations and modular curves, and he proves that their moduli space M 2 is 1\u2212dimensional and it is isomorphic to the coarse moduli space of elliptic curves. Therefore one wonders whether it is possible to characterize M 2 as a subvariety of the moduli space M described by Catanese and Ciliberto. This is equivalent to characterize the elements in |D 0 | with at worst R.D.P. as singularities and containing a genus 2 pencil. Our solution is (cf. Theorem 7.1) Theorem B. There is exactly one divisor X \u2208 |D 0 | containing a genus 2 pencil, and it is smooth. Moreover, let \u03be i be any 2\u2212torsion point of E different from zero, and consider the curve:",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "122502903"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "122502903": {
      "title": "Surfaces fibr\u00e9es en courbes de genre deux",
      "abstract": "A tennis practice device which uses a hollow container which may be filled with sand or water as an anchor for a tennis ball attached to the lid of the container by means of an elongated elastic line. The line is attached to the tennis ball by means of a nylon adapter line which is threaded through the ball and tied in a loop. The elastic line is attached to the lid by means of a swivel hook. The device provides a completely portable tennis practice apparatus which may be filled with a weighty material during use and which serves as a storage container for the tennis ball and line when it is not in use."
    }
